def detect_outliers(column):
    Q1 = column.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = column.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    return (column < lower_bound) | (column > upper_bound)

outliers_mpg = detect_outliers(df_cleaned['MPG'])
outliers_hp = detect_outliers(df_cleaned['Horsepower'])
outliers_weight = detect_outliers(df_cleaned['Weight'])

print(f"outliers in MPG: {outliers_mpg.sum()}")
print(f"outliers in Horsepower: {outliers_hp.sum()}")
print(f"outliers in Weight: {outliers_weight.sum()}")

print("\noutliers in MPG:")
print(df_cleaned[outliers_mpg]['MPG'])

df_no_outliers = df_cleaned[~(outliers_mpg | outliers_hp | outliers_weight)].copy()

How has average vehicle fuel efficiency changed from 1970 to 1982, and what trends are visible?¶

In [64]:
df_no_outliers['Full_Year'] = 1900 + df_no_outliers['Model']

mpg_by_year = df_no_outliers.groupby('Full_Year')['MPG'].mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(11, 5))
mpg_by_year.plot(kind='line', marker='o')
plt.title('The evolution of average fuel consumption over the years')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('AVG MPG')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Insights:¶

A clear upward trend shows steady MPG improvement from ~15 (1970) to ~30 (1982), suggesting automotive industry focus on fuel efficiency¶

Two distinct growth phases:¶

Slow improvement (1970-1974)¶

Accelerated gains (1975-1982), likely reflecting oil crisis impacts and new regulations¶

No major regressions indicate consistent technological progress despite market fluctuations¶

Insights:¶

Clear efficiency hierarchy:¶

4-cylinder engines deliver highest MPG (25-40 range)¶

6-cylinder engines show moderate efficiency (15-25 MPG)¶

8-cylinder engines are least efficient (mostly below 20 MPG)¶

Performance trade-offs:¶

The MPG "sweet spot" appears at 4 cylinders¶

Each additional cylinder reduces efficiency by ~5-10 MPG on average¶

Notable exceptions:¶

Some 6-cylinder outliers match 4-cylinder efficiency¶

Minimal 3-cylinder data points suggest emerging small-engine technology¶

Practical Implication: Consumers prioritizing fuel economy should favor 4-cylinder vehicles, while those needing power must accept lower MPG.¶

# Correlation Matrix
corr_matrix = df_no_outliers[numeric_cols].corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', center=0)
plt.title('Correlation Matrix of Numerical Variables')
plt.show()

Insights:¶

MPG shows strongest inverse correlations with:¶

Cylinders (-0.76): More cylinders = lower efficiency¶

Displacement (-0.73): Larger engines = worse MPG¶

Weight (-0.78): Heavier vehicles = less efficient¶

Engine parameters are highly interdependent:¶

Cylinders ↔ Displacement (0.96)¶

Cylinders ↔ Horsepower (0.86)¶

Weight ↔ Horsepower (0.85)¶

Acceleration has weak relationships:¶

Slight positive with MPG (0.4)¶

Mild inverse with cylinders (-0.5)¶

Key Takeaway: Fuel efficiency is primarily determined by engine size (cylinders/displacement) and vehicle weight, not acceleration performance.¶
